        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>City pages</strong> are location-specific landing pages that target a particular city's search queries — helping businesses rank for <strong>"[service] in [city]"</strong> keywords. Each city page must contain genuinely unique content: shared templates with only the city name swapped trigger Google's doorway-page penalty. A Moz study found city pages with <strong>70%+ unique content rank 3 to 5 positions higher</strong> than template-only pages.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Target keyword</div>
            <div class="tms-value">[service] in [city]</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Uniqueness target</div>
            <div class="tms-value">60–70%+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Typical volume</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5–20 pages</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">City pages are how a service-area business rank for cities it doesn't have offices in. They're also how a service-area business gets buried when Google decides those pages are doorways. The line between the two is genuinely unique content, not template gymnastics.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are city pages?</h2>
        <p>A city page is a dedicated landing page optimized for the search intent of a single city where the business operates or provides services. A plumber serving the Dallas–Fort Worth metroplex might build pages for Dallas, Fort Worth, Arlington, Plano, Frisco, and McKinney — each uniquely optimized for its local keywords, testimonials, and service context.</p>
        <p>Typical elements on a strong city page:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>City-named H1</strong> targeting the primary local keyword</li>
          <li><strong>Local team or crew assignment</strong> for that service area</li>
          <li><strong>Area-specific testimonials and case studies</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Local pricing or service details</strong> where they differ</li>
          <li><strong>Neighborhood-level content</strong> — nearby areas served, well-known landmarks</li>
          <li><strong>LocalBusiness schema</strong> and an embedded map centered on the city</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's rule on doorway pages</div>
          <p>Google's search documentation explicitly warns against doorway pages — nearly identical pages differing only by geographic target. The practical test: <strong>if removing the city name from two pages makes them indistinguishable, Google treats them as doorways</strong> and can suppress or de-index the entire set.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why city pages matter for SEO</h2>
        <p>Four reasons city pages remain the backbone of service-area SEO in 2026:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Geographic keyword coverage.</strong> Ranking for "plumber Dallas" and "plumber Plano" requires separate URLs Google can attribute to each city — a single homepage can't rank for both.</li>
          <li><strong>Service-area reach.</strong> Businesses without a physical office in every city still capture searches in those cities via city pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Local pack support.</strong> While city pages rank in organic results, not the pack itself, the topical relevance signals reinforce Google Business Profile visibility for cities where you do have a listing.</li>
          <li><strong>Traffic multiplication.</strong> 10 city pages, each ranking for their local variant, deliver an order-of-magnitude more organic traffic than a single generic homepage.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How city pages work in practice</h2>
        <p>Three pillars: unique content, local SEO optimization, and doorway avoidance.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># URL structure examples</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">/plumbing-dallas/</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> single-service-per-city<br>
          <span class="uf-new">/service-areas/dallas/</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> multi-service-per-city hub<br>
          <span class="uf-new">/dallas-tx/water-heater-repair/</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> city-then-service<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Uniqueness signals to include</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">·</span> City-specific testimonials with real names + neighborhood<br>
          <span class="uf-label">·</span> Local team assignment with headshots<br>
          <span class="uf-label">·</span> Weather / seasonality relevant to the city<br>
          <span class="uf-label">·</span> Pricing variation by area (if applicable)<br>
          <span class="uf-label">·</span> Community involvement, sponsorships, local events
        </div>

        <h3>Content differentiation</h3>
        <p>Beyond the city name in a template, real differentiation includes area-specific testimonials, local team headshots, city-specific service details (Austin's summer AC failures vs Round Rock's insulation issues), and neighborhood mentions the customer would recognize.</p>

        <h3>SEO optimization</h3>
        <p>Target 2–3 primary local keywords per page. Include the city name in the title tag, H1, URL slug, and meta description. Add LocalBusiness or Service schema markup and embed a Google Map centered on the target city. Interlink to <a href="/glossary/neighborhood-pages/">neighborhood pages</a> where they exist.</p>

        <h3>Avoiding the doorway trap</h3>
        <p>Add local photos, area-specific pricing where it varies, genuine local knowledge, and testimonials tied to real customers in the city. The "remove the city name" test is the fastest self-check: if two pages become indistinguishable, they're doorways.</p>

        <h2 id="types">City page structures compared</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
