        <h2 id="examples">Real city page examples</h2>

        <h3>1. HVAC company with 12 city pages</h3>
        <p>The Austin page discusses extreme summer heat and AC failures typical in older East Austin homes. The Round Rock page covers newer-construction insulation challenges and different service call profiles. Each page reflects genuine local knowledge — same service, materially different content — and each ranks on page 1 for its city variant.</p>

        <h3>2. Legal firm aligned to jurisdictions</h3>
        <p>A DUI attorney builds pages aligned to court jurisdictions rather than arbitrary cities. Each page discusses the specific court process, judge preferences, DUI penalty ranges, and local resources for that jurisdiction. Because the content is jurisdiction-specific, the pages are inherently unique.</p>

        <h3>3. Plumbing multi-service hub</h3>
        <p>A plumber uses a hub-and-spoke pattern: <code>/dallas-plumbing/</code> as the city hub, with linked service pages for water heater repair, drain cleaning, and re-piping specific to Dallas customers. Each hub-and-spoke set carries unique testimonials from that metro.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">City pages vs neighborhood pages — different granularity</h2>
        <p>Both are location-targeted landing pages. The difference is scope and intent.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use city pages when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Targeting metro-area searches ("plumber Dallas")</li>
              <li>Serving a small number (5–20) of distinct cities</li>
              <li>Building initial local SEO coverage</li>
              <li>Establishing service-area presence for a new region</li>
              <li>City is the primary geographic granularity searchers use</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use neighborhood pages when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Targeting hyper-local queries ("plumber Uptown Dallas")</li>
              <li>Already ranking for the city and going deeper</li>
              <li>City is too large to serve with one page</li>
              <li>Neighborhoods have distinct service profiles</li>
              <li>Long-tail expansion after city pages rank</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for city pages</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>One page per city you actually serve.</strong> Do not build pages for cities you cannot service — Google detects deceptive geographic targeting.</li>
          <li><strong>60%+ unique content per page.</strong> Moz research shows 70%+ ranks 3–5 positions higher than template-only pages. Aim for 70%.</li>
          <li><strong>Include real local proof.</strong> Testimonials with real names and neighborhoods, local team headshots, photos from actual jobs in that city.</li>
          <li><strong>City name in title, H1, URL, meta.</strong> Consistent on-page signals across every crawlable element.</li>
          <li><strong>Add LocalBusiness or Service schema.</strong> Structured data reinforces the location relevance for search engines.</li>
          <li><strong>Interlink to neighborhood pages and back.</strong> Topical clustering strengthens the whole city hub's authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Apply the "remove city name" test.</strong> If two pages become indistinguishable when you strip the city, rewrite before publishing.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — scaling to 100 doorway pages</div>
          <p>The moment scaling requires copy-paste city pages, the SEO gain flips negative. Google's doorway filter treats the set as manipulative and can suppress or de-index the whole cluster. Cap at the number of cities you can meaningfully differentiate.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common city page mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Template with only city name swapped</strong> — the classic doorway pattern</li>
          <li><strong>Pages for cities you don't serve</strong> — deceptive and detectable</li>
          <li><strong>No unique testimonials</strong> — every proof point becomes generic</li>
          <li><strong>Same photos across every city page</strong> — visual signals also count for uniqueness</li>
          <li><strong>Thin content padded to hit word count</strong> — Google reads padding as low quality</li>
          <li><strong>No internal linking to / from city pages</strong> — orphan pages don't accrue authority</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping schema</strong> — missing the local relevance signal</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
